\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:6}
Based on the asymptotic expansion formula of far-field pattern in the existence of small electromagnetic inhomogeneities, the structure of subspace migration imaging function is investigated when the applied frequency is inexact to the true one. Based on the relationship with Bessel functions of order zero and one of the first kind, we have confirmed the reason as to why the locations of inhomogeneities identified inaccurately.

In this paper, we considered the detection of inhomogeneities in the full-view inverse scattering problem. Based on the difficulties from \cite{PL2,P-SUB5,AIL1}, extension to the limited-view or half-space problem will be an remarkable research subject. Furthermore, we expect it can be extended to the various inverse scattering problem in three-dimension.

